Two sections: top detailed view March 20 to April 25 2021 with y-axis 0-300, bottom broader overview March 2020 to April 2021 y-axis 0-4000. So it's a broken y-axis (split axis) or discontinuous axis: top zoomed view and bottom overview. This can be misleading if not clearly indicated, as it can exaggerate differences. However the description says chart is divided into two sections, top detailed view, bottom broader overview. That is a "broken axis" which can be considered a truncated axis or "dual axis"? It's not a dual axis (two separate y scales) but a split axis (break). That can be considered truncated axis or perhaps "dual axis" error type? Actually truncated axis is when axis does not start at zero. Here bottom axis starts at 0, top axis starts at 0 but limited to 0-300. The issue is that the two sections are juxtaposed, could mislead about the magnitude of change? They have separate y scales, could be considered "dual axis" (multiple y axes on same chart). The error list includes "Dual axis" defined as more than 1 vertical axis on same chart (does not include 2 charts side-by-side). This fits: they have two sections with different y-axes. So that could be considered dual axis. Also "Cherry-picking"? They highlight a specific period March 20-April 25 2021 with zoom; may be fine. The caption mentions 'Patients in hospital' and 'Patients in ventilation beds' not shown: that's mismatch but not necessarily a visualization error, but the analysis notes confidence reduction.

The top zoomed axis starts at zero as well but limited to 300 which is appropriate for that period.

Is there any other error? The title says "Patients Admitted to Hospital", but the caption also includes "Patients in ventilation beds" not shown; could be incomplete data representation (Information Access Rhetoric). Not necessarily misleading, but incomplete.

Thus I think there is a potential misleading aspect: Dual axis (different y scales) can mislead perception of trend magnitude; also possibly cherry-picking because focusing on recent decline.

Assess intention: likely unintentional; common practice to show zoomed view. So intentional? I'd say likely unintentional.
